			<h2>If you&#8217;re dealing with one of these, we&#8217;ve probably been there before</h2>
<h3>You’ve got an idea but no software yet</h3>
<p>You need a partner who’ll help you scope what you’re actually building, give you a fixed-price quote you can trust, and deliver something you can put in front of users without it falling over. We work with founders launching a first product and businesses adding software to a service that’s always run on spreadsheets.</p>

<h3>Your existing software is slowing the business down</h3>
<p>Every change feels risky. The code is fragile, the original team is gone, and you can’t tell whether to patch it, replace it, or live with it. We’ve worked through that question with several businesses – it’s rarely as binary as it sounds. Sometimes the right answer is a careful rework of the parts that hurt most. Sometimes it’s a clean rebuild. We’ll tell you which, and why – <a href="/case-studies.html">see case studies</a>.</p>

<h3>Your team needs a steady pair of hands</h3>
<p>You’ve got engineers who are competent but stretched, or a project that needs a senior developer alongside them for six months. We embed alongside your people rather than working in isolation, so your team learns what we know as we go. When we leave, the software is yours to maintain – not a black box that needs us to keep running.</p>

<h3>What we tend to build</h3>
<ul>
<li>Customer portals and self-service tools</li>
<li>Mobile apps for iOS and Android</li>
<li>CRMs and internal dashboards</li>
<li>Data migration and process automation</li>
<li>APIs and integrations</li>
<li>Search-backed applications and reporting tools</li>
</ul>

<h3>How we build it</h3>
<p><strong>C#, .NET, and Azure.</strong> We work primarily in the Microsoft stack and have done since .NET arrived. Azure lets us build, test, and deploy modular applications quickly – releasing features as soon as they’re ready, rather than waiting for a big-bang launch. Early feedback usually changes the shape of what comes next, and our pipeline is set up for that.</p>

<p><strong>Data and storage.</strong> The right database depends on what you’re storing and how you’ll query it. We’ve used <strong>SQL Server</strong> for relational systems, <strong>MongoDB</strong> for document-heavy applications where read performance matters, and <strong>Elasticsearch</strong> for search and analytics over large datasets. The right answer is often a combination – SQL as the source of truth, with copies into MongoDB or Elasticsearch optimised for the queries the front end actually makes.</p>

<p><strong>API design.</strong> APIs sit at the heart of most modern systems. A well-designed API is stable, well-documented, and easy to use. A poorly-designed one becomes the bottleneck nobody wants to touch. We’ve built APIs that serve web applications, integrate partner systems, and underpin microservice architectures – and we’ll tell you straight if microservices aren’t actually the right answer for what you’re trying to do.</p>

<p><strong>Web UI.</strong> For browser-based applications we use <strong>Next.js</strong> (React) when SEO or a rich front-end ecosystem matters, and <strong>Blazor</strong> when keeping the whole stack in C# is the right call – often the better fit for internal tools where the team already lives in .NET.</p>

<p><strong>Mobile.</strong> When a project needs an app on both iOS and Android, we build with <strong>React Native</strong> (via Expo) so a single codebase ships to both stores without compromising on the native feel. We did exactly this for HWWA Consulting’s <a href="/case-studies/benefits-buddy.html">Benefits Buddy</a> – a mobile-first employee benefits platform delivered alongside a .NET back office and Azure infrastructure.</p>

<p>If your stack is something else (Node, Python, Java, Go), we’ll tell you upfront whether we can help. Honesty about fit beats pretending we know everything.</p>
			
